So there's a fair amount of my
personal information in the

00:36:19.529 --> 00:36:21.974
next few slides so please
try to pay attention.

00:36:21.974 --> 00:36:22.609
JOHN ZERATSKY: Get
your notebooks ready.

00:36:22.959 --> 00:36:23.699
MATT SHOBE: Yep.

00:36:23.849 --> 00:36:29.169
So 23 Skidoo Street-- so in
this case you could make sure

00:36:29.169 --> 00:36:32.139
that if somebody has the
password field and is typing

00:36:32.139 --> 00:36:34.829
in it, don't take the focus
from the password field.

00:36:34.829 --> 00:36:36.479
Something you wouldn't think
about because you're like, oh

00:36:36.479 --> 00:36:37.119
we're going to set
the name field.

00:36:37.119 --> 00:36:38.650
Nobody's ever going to get
ahead of it, but in practice if

00:36:38.650 --> 00:36:40.609
the system works with the
timing in such a way that this

00:36:40.609 --> 00:36:42.619
can happen you need to make
sure that you handle

00:36:42.619 --> 00:36:44.789
that sort of thing.

00:36:44.789 --> 00:36:46.810
So messy data entry.

00:36:46.810 --> 00:36:50.110
Why force me to enter the
parens and the em-dash

00:36:50.110 --> 00:36:50.820
or the dash-em-dash.

00:36:50.820 --> 00:36:53.700
Or the dash or the http prefix
if you need to give me a

00:36:53.700 --> 00:36:55.490
website address or I need to
give you a website address.

00:36:55.740 --> 00:36:59.344
Or in I think a number of
cases, I don't even need to

00:36:59.344 --> 00:37:01.099
indicate it's a Visa, I
can just start typing the

00:37:01.099 --> 00:37:03.130
credit card number, you're
going to figure it out.

00:37:03.130 --> 00:37:05.919
If you can do this sort of
stuff for data entry,

00:37:05.919 --> 00:37:09.419
especially repetitive stuff--
people are in here doing this

00:37:09.419 --> 00:37:12.219
every day and it's not like a
one-time account setup feature,

00:37:12.219 --> 00:37:14.129
even then you still want to do
it because I just want to make

00:37:14.129 --> 00:37:17.559
it as quick as possible for you
to fill out this form and not

00:37:17.559 --> 00:37:20.619
throw an error message, cause a
failure to happen that we

00:37:20.619 --> 00:37:22.489
didn't need to validate for.

00:37:23.159 --> 00:37:25.910
Make messy data entry as
possible as it can be for

00:37:25.910 --> 00:37:28.229
the user and it'll
make them happier.

00:37:28.229 --> 00:37:30.710
Again, this is kind of
empathy sneaking in here.

00:37:30.710 --> 00:37:33.259
Is that you've tried to
absolutely make sure that bare

00:37:33.259 --> 00:37:36.150
minimum error cases are the
ones that you're going to

00:37:36.150 --> 00:37:39.729
report on and stop somebody
from making progress.

00:37:39.729 --> 00:37:44.290
I like this particular example
just because it shows kind

00:37:44.290 --> 00:37:46.219
of readiness for anything.

00:37:46.219 --> 00:37:49.710
BBC always has a high and low
graphics version of I think

00:37:49.710 --> 00:37:50.810
all their major new sections.

00:37:50.810 --> 00:37:52.499
I'm not sure how
deep this goes.

00:37:52.499 --> 00:37:54.929
The low graphics version will
render on just about any

00:37:54.929 --> 00:37:56.829
device, which is nice to
have generally speaking.

00:37:56.829 --> 00:37:59.939
You almost always know you
can go to slash low there

00:37:59.939 --> 00:38:02.259
and get to that content.

00:38:02.259 --> 00:38:04.519
The high graphics version of
course is whatever bells and

00:38:04.519 --> 00:38:06.660
whistles they care to deploy.

00:38:06.959 --> 00:38:08.769
But let's say there's a
bandwidth spike, there's a

00:38:08.769 --> 00:38:12.229
major news story, something big
is coming, let's say you're

00:38:12.229 --> 00:38:14.400
about to do a major product
announcement and you know your

00:38:14.400 --> 00:38:15.549
homepage is going
to get slammed.

00:38:15.549 --> 00:38:18.750
You might just want to have
a plan B homepage that

00:38:18.750 --> 00:38:20.690
makes sure that the news
still gets through.

00:38:20.690 --> 00:38:23.060
It seems obvious, but plenty
of times people don't

00:38:23.060 --> 00:38:23.450
think about it.

00:38:23.450 --> 00:38:25.339
They don't prepare for this
particular kind of failure,

00:38:25.339 --> 00:38:27.960
which in this case is something
that could've been very good,

00:38:27.960 --> 00:38:30.239
goes horribly wrong because
you weren't ready for it.

00:38:30.239 --> 00:38:33.069
And having that alternative
case ready to go could save

00:38:33.069 --> 00:38:35.999
you a lot of heartache.

