00:39:40.429 --> 00:39:43.969
JOHN ZERATSKY: Which
is to be reliable.

00:39:43.969 --> 00:39:46.839
In a sense we've kind of
brought this presentation

00:39:46.839 --> 00:39:47.599
full circle.

00:39:47.599 --> 00:39:50.730
I started out by talking about
latency, which is a technical

00:39:50.730 --> 00:39:54.430
factor that has a big effect
on the user experience.

00:39:54.430 --> 00:39:56.249
Reliability is the same way.

00:39:56.249 --> 00:39:58.640
Nothing's more aggravating
than software that crashes

00:39:58.640 --> 00:40:01.079
or a website that goes
down unexpectedly.

00:40:01.079 --> 00:40:03.040
Especially when it's something
that you really rely on.

00:40:03.040 --> 00:40:05.000
Of course, the stakes
are higher for certain

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:05.980
types of applications.

00:40:05.980 --> 00:40:08.859
You know, we've talked a
lot about banking and

00:40:08.859 --> 00:40:09.999
those sorts of things.

00:40:09.999 --> 00:40:14.879
If your banks website is
unavailable or acting sort of

00:40:14.879 --> 00:40:17.069
erratically, not only are you
not going to trust that

00:40:17.069 --> 00:40:19.830
website, you might actually
not trust the bank, right?

00:40:19.830 --> 00:40:23.130
So this sort of thing could
have a really huge impact on

00:40:23.130 --> 00:40:26.139
that company's reputation.

00:40:26.139 --> 00:40:29.799
And as Matt mentioned, to sort
of flip this Twitter example on

00:40:29.799 --> 00:40:33.579
its head, you know, the fail
whale and their error page that

00:40:33.579 --> 00:40:37.870
was very nice to look at, it
