You know, generally a button's
going to be heavier visually

00:44:40.190 --> 00:44:42.969
than a link, so people are
going to see it and recognize

00:44:42.969 --> 00:44:44.709
that as the primary action.

00:44:45.390 --> 00:44:48.849
And finally, just the simple
matter of click target

00:44:48.849 --> 00:44:49.680
and size, right?

00:44:49.680 --> 00:44:53.539
A big button is going to be
easier to click than a small

00:44:53.539 --> 00:44:55.449
cancel link and so you don't
want people accidentally

00:44:55.449 --> 00:44:57.469
hitting that cancel link.

00:44:57.469 --> 00:44:59.519
If you had two buttons that
were the same size right next

00:44:59.519 --> 00:45:02.819
to each other it'd be pretty
easy to either mess up and hit

00:45:02.819 --> 00:45:05.020
the wrong one or you know,
you'd have to sit there and

00:45:05.020 --> 00:45:06.910
sort of squint and say,
OK which one's the one I

00:45:06.910 --> 00:45:08.049
really want in this case?

00:45:08.049 --> 00:45:12.539
AUDIENCE: OK, a Google specific
question, do you guys actually

00:45:12.539 --> 00:45:15.189
use like usability test labs
and actually run your users

00:45:15.189 --> 00:45:17.789
through visual experience like
iTracking and things like that?

00:45:17.789 --> 00:45:19.659
MATT SHOBE: Yeah, definitely.

00:45:19.659 --> 00:45:20.749
JOHN ZERATSKY: At Google
we do the full gamut

00:45:20.749 --> 00:45:21.719
of user research.

00:45:21.719 --> 00:45:26.490
From very tactical, specific
usability testing and iTracking

00:45:26.490 --> 00:45:31.400
all the way to ethnographic
studies where we just go to

00:45:31.400 --> 00:45:33.133
somebody's office or go to
somebody's home and talk and

00:45:33.133 --> 00:45:34.369
talk to them about how
their using products.

00:45:35.239 --> 00:45:37.529
MATT SHOBE: And paper
prototypes and show a series of

00:45:37.529 --> 00:45:40.099
my mocks and have people just
look around a conference

00:45:40.099 --> 00:45:41.169
room in an afternoon.

00:45:41.169 --> 00:45:43.489
Very scrappy stuff, too.

00:45:43.489 --> 00:45:46.999
AUDIENCE: I noticed like my
users in my labs are actually

00:45:46.999 --> 00:45:49.079
kind of put off on the fact
that they're in a lab, but

00:45:49.079 --> 00:45:52.179
whenever I get way better
results from anything

00:45:52.179 --> 00:45:52.645
I resolved.

00:45:53.579 --> 00:45:56.312
JOHN ZERATSKY: Yeah, we didn't
really talk about research here

00:45:56.312 --> 00:46:00.499
and I kind of wish we had a
little bit, but it's

00:46:00.499 --> 00:46:02.269
important to sort of have a
good cross-section.

00:46:02.269 --> 00:46:04.660
You don't want to be overly
reliant on one research

00:46:04.660 --> 00:46:06.910
technique or it's going to
affect the results

00:46:06.910 --> 00:46:07.490
that you get.

00:46:07.490 --> 00:46:09.629
AUDIENCE: I'm guessing you
guys are huge on remote

00:46:09.629 --> 00:46:09.869
usability testing.

