00:49:03.574 --> 00:49:06.679
like that, so how would you
compare that when you're

00:49:06.679 --> 00:49:09.689
designing for kids compared to
when you're designing

00:49:09.689 --> 00:49:11.219
for adults?

00:49:11.219 --> 00:49:14.369
JOHN ZERATSKY: Well, nobody
pays attention to instructions.

00:49:14.369 --> 00:49:16.009
MATT SHOBE: I was going to say,
kids might actually do a better

00:49:16.009 --> 00:49:19.039
job of reading the instructions
than any of us do.

00:49:19.039 --> 00:49:20.419
JOHN ZERATSKY: That's not
something I have any experience

00:49:20.419 --> 00:49:22.129
with unfortunately.

00:49:22.859 --> 00:49:25.127
AUDIENCE: Any references
or ideas you think

00:49:25.127 --> 00:49:27.001
is helpful for that?

00:49:27.939 --> 00:49:29.459
JOHN ZERATSKY: You're probably
already aware of this, but I

00:49:29.459 --> 00:49:33.019
know there has been an
explosion of applications

00:49:33.019 --> 00:49:35.150
targeted at children,
especially for the iPhone and

00:49:35.150 --> 00:49:39.249
iPad just because it's such
an immediate interface.

00:49:39.989 --> 00:49:41.879
I'm sure you're familiar
with many of those.

00:49:41.879 --> 00:49:44.149
I would look there just to
see some examples of what

00:49:44.149 --> 00:49:45.730
other people are doing.

00:49:45.730 --> 00:49:47.247
AUDIENCE: OK, thanks.

00:49:55.849 --> 00:50:01.179
AUDIENCE: Hi, some Google
website uses unexpected results

00:50:01.179 --> 00:50:04.819
such as if you search something
on Google Maps for instance,

00:50:04.819 --> 00:50:09.979
get you directions from New
York to Paris it says like swim

00:50:09.979 --> 00:50:18.499
10,000 miles or I think it used
to be at Google Search when you

00:50:18.499 --> 00:50:20.376
search for Chuck Norris it says
you don't find Chuck Norris

00:50:20.376 --> 00:50:20.859
he finds you or something.

00:50:20.859 --> 00:50:21.339
JOHN ZERATSKY: Right.

00:50:22.219 --> 00:50:24.257
AUDIENCE: So what do you
think about that kind

00:50:24.257 --> 00:50:25.325
of user experience?

00:50:25.859 --> 00:50:28.539
MATT SHOBE: I'm for it.

00:50:30.579 --> 00:50:34.789
As long as it doesn't get in
the way of something that's

00:50:34.789 --> 00:50:36.450
life-threatening or mission
critical or high,

00:50:36.450 --> 00:50:37.390
high frequency.

00:50:37.390 --> 00:50:38.940
Nobody likes to hear
the same joke.

00:50:38.940 --> 00:50:40.880
And you're not probably going
to run that same query 59 time.

00:50:40.880 --> 00:50:42.539
Although you might be
interested to see if you get

00:50:42.539 --> 00:50:43.240
different instructions.

00:50:43.560 --> 00:50:45.880
This time try it butterfly
instead of back stroke.

00:50:45.880 --> 00:50:46.779
That sort of thing.

00:50:50.309 --> 00:50:53.349
That's actually one thing from
the be surprising principle

00:50:53.349 --> 00:50:57.049
that we mentioned-- I forgot to
touch on, which is easter eggs.

00:50:57.049 --> 00:51:01.900
Little in jokes when the right
things combined can be fun as

00:51:01.900 --> 00:51:04.299
long as there sort of whimsical
and off to the side and don't

00:51:04.299 --> 00:51:06.320
get in the way of whatever
the critical thing is

00:51:06.320 --> 00:51:07.519
that you're doing.

00:51:07.519 --> 00:51:10.939
And in this case you know I
think those searches are not

00:51:10.939 --> 00:51:15.085
super critical although I guess
you could decide-- I'm not

00:51:15.085 --> 00:51:16.450
sure how you actually
opt out of those.

00:51:16.450 --> 00:51:19.010
JOHN ZERATSKY: Yes, so I think
in the case of the Maps one is

00:51:19.010 --> 00:51:22.510
a really, really good one
because you're realistically

00:51:22.510 --> 00:51:24.240
not going to use Google Maps
to figure out how to get

00:51:24.240 --> 00:51:25.300
from New York to Paris.

00:51:26.489 --> 00:51:30.109
It's not a realistic of use of
that tool, so that's a perfect

00:51:30.109 --> 00:51:31.759
opportunity to inject a
little bit of humor.

00:51:31.759 --> 00:51:35.520
The Chuck Norris thing, like as
long as the real search results

00:51:35.520 --> 00:51:38.400
are also on the page, you know,
let's say you're actually doing

00:51:38.400 --> 00:51:40.659
research about Chuck Norris
for some legitimate purpose.

00:51:40.659 --> 00:51:42.119
You know, you don't want
to be blocked from

00:51:42.119 --> 00:51:43.050
finding the results.

00:51:44.060 --> 00:51:45.640
It's just fun.

00:51:46.279 --> 00:51:47.769
MATT SHOBE: We'll make sure
the scholarly reports

00:51:47.769 --> 00:51:49.329
still get through.

00:51:51.350 --> 00:51:54.527
The awesomeness side is fun
to future up top if you can.

00:51:57.329 --> 00:52:00.160
JOHN ZERATSKY: OK, I think
we've warned you down.

